Ternary Search


Sorting: Arranging elements in some order.

Types:
i)Comparison based: In these algorithm, elements are sorted by
comparing two values at a time.

  Bubble sort, Insertion sort, Selection sort, Merge sort, Quick sort

Time complexity: O(n*n) to O(n log n)  
  
ii)Non comparison based: These algorithms does not compare elements directly, instead. they
use mathematical properties like digit position or frequency.

  Counting sort, Radix sort, Bucket sort

Time complexity: O(n) or near linear

iii) Stable sorting: A sorting algorithm is stable if  equal elements maintain their original 
order after sorting.


Alice - 25
Bob - 30
carol - 25


Alice - 25
carol - 25
Bob - 30

  Bubble sort, Insertion sort, Merge sort
  
iv)Unstable sorting:  A sorting algorithm is unstable if equal elements may change order.
 selection sort, quick sort
 
v)Internal Sorting: Sorting done when the entire data fits into main memory(RAM).

 Quick, Merge, Heap 
 
 Fast, No disk access required, used in most apps
 
vi)External Sorting:Used when the data is too large to fit in memory and stored in disk/files.

 External merge sort
 
 Working:
  a)Data is divided into chunks
  b)Each chunk is stored in memory
  c)Then merged from disk

Use case: Big databases, processing systems 

 
 
   Bubble sort:
   
   [5,1,4,2,8]
   
   Pass 1: [1,5,4,2,8] [1,4,5,2,8] [1,4,2,5,8]
   pass 2: [1,2,4,5,8]
   pass 3: no swap
   
Insertion Sort: It is a simple sorting algorithm that builds the
final sorting array one element at a time.

How it works:
 We divide the array into two parts:
  i)Sorted part(left side)
  ii)Unsorted part(right side)
  
  We pick one element from the unsorted part and place it at the
  correct position in the sorted part.
  
  [5, 2, 9, 1, 5]
  
 Pass 1: Take 2  - compare it with 5 - Shift 5 - insert 2 
         [2,5,9,1,5]
 pass 2:  Take 9 - already in correct position [2,5,9,1,5]
 pass 3: Take 1 - shift 9,5,2 - insert 1 [1,2,5,9,5]  
 pass 4: Take 5 - already in correct position - [1,2,5,5,9]    
 
 
 Selection Sort: 
 It works by repeatedly finding the minimum(maximum) element from
 the unsorted part and placing it at the beginning.
 
 
 How works:
  we divide the array into:
   i)Sorted Part(left)
   ii)Unsorted part(right)
   
   At each step:
    1. Find the smallest in the unsorted part.
    2. Swap it with the first element of the unsorted part.
    3. Move the boundary of the sorted part one step right.
    
   
   [64,25,12,22,11]
   
   Pass 1: Find smallest in the whole array - 11 - swap it with the
   		   first element	 
           [11,25,12,22,64]
           
   Pass 2: Find smallest in remaining part - 12 - swap it with 25
           [11,12,25,22,64]
   pass 3:  Find smallest - 22 - swap it with 25
           [11,12,22,25,64]
   pass 4:  no change already sorted              

   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
  
   
    